Let A, B, C, D, and E represent the number of miles each runner ran.
\begin{align*}
A+B+C+D+E&=100\\
A+B+C+D&=90\\
\text{So, }A+B+C+D+E&=A+B+C+D+10\\
\text{Which implies that }90&=A+B+C+D\\
\text{Since Runner B's portion is }1.5\text{ times the length of Runner A's portion,}\\
B=1.5A.\\
\text{Also, the combined portion for Runners C and D is twice the length of the combined portion for Runners A and B,}\\
C+D=2(A+B).
\end{align*}
Substitute $B=1.5A$ and $C+D=2(A+B)$ into the equation $A+B+C+D=90.$
Substitute $B=1.5A$ and $C+D=2(A+B)$ into the equation $A+B+C+D=90$ to get
\begin{align*}
A+B+C+D&=90\\
A+(1.5A)+2(A+B)&=90\\
A+1.5A+2A+2(1.5A)&=90\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 6.5A+3A&=90
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
6.5A+3A&=90\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 9.5A&=90
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
9.5A&=90\\
\Rightarrow\qquad A&=90/9.5=\frac{90}{95/10}=\frac{900}{95}
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
A&=\frac{900}{95}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad B&=1.5A=\frac{1350}{95}
\end{align*}
